#text:
NEW YORK (CBS.MW)
    -- June
    palladium
rebounded late in the session, slightly rising past the price of gold

.
    Volume in the palladium market is light as the Russian State Duma votes again Friday on
    Sergei Kiriyenko's nomination as prime minister. Kiriyenko was nominated by Russian
    President Boris Yeltsin after Yeltsin fired his entire cabinet in March. Analysts warn
    that if the Duma votes down Kiriyenko for a third time, the delay in metals exports may
    extend into the third quarter of the year.
    Palladium rose the extended daily limit, $12.00 in early trade, then plunged the down-side
    limit amid reports Kiriyenko is gaining support.

Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: New investors overly optimistic?

PARAGRAPH.STRONG:
Investment Company
    Institute
#text:
As speculators continue to push a Dow 10,000, mutual fund
    investors are pouring more and more cash into stock funds. The

reports that $24.2 billion was invested in stock funds in February, a
    65 percent increase from the January total. Assets for the whole fund industry, including
    stock, bond, municipal, and money market funds stand at $4.8 trillion. As popularity
    in funds and investor optimism flourish, anxious mutual fund industry executives wonder
    how to alert their shareholders to a bear market potential. The problem is that millions
    of neophyte investors jumped into funds in the last year or so. Surveys indicate that many
    think double-digit total returns are the norm, that funds are insured by the government,
    and that stocks rarely go down very much.

PARAGRAPH.#text:
America Online's stock jumped 3.7 percent Monday after the
    company told money managers that advertising revenue is soaring thanks to rising
    readership and rates. Chief Financial Officer Len Leader said the company's ad revenue has
    the potential to exceed $3.1 billion this year if the Internet service provider sold out
    its ads. While only theoretical, the figure illustrates the rapidly increasing importance
    of advertising sales to the Dulles, Va.-based company. AOL, with fiscal 1997 sales
    totaling only $1.69 billion, is projected to generate about $2.51 billion in the fiscal
    year ending this June. Advertising sales reached $108.8 million last year, nearly double

Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: Bonding with bonds?

#text:
For those that found comfort in bond funds when the markets went for a
    joy ride during the past few months, next week's Time magazine has a warning: bond funds
    may not be what you think they are. "Bond-fund risk is just not well
    understood," says
, an economist with the

. While bond funds do invest in bonds, they don't behave like
    them. They cannot guarantee return of principal because they never actually mature,
    returns are tied as much to daily price movement as to the interest rate they pay, and
    income generated by the fund isn't fixed - it fluctuates with market rates.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Bonding with bonds?

Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: Taxing capital gains headaches

#text: Be ready for "several waves of panic," warns

,
    vice president at

, a record keeping service for more than 235
    mutual fund companies. Gore is referring to the filling out of your 1997 tax return and
    dealing with the headaches that mutual fund capital gains are likely to create. One
    sure cause for anxiety, reported the Wall Street Journal Friday, is the sudden realization
    that the loser fund in your portfolio may also be hit by a capital gains tax. According to
    fund trackers at Morningstar, Invesco
    Asian Growth

had a capital gain of nearly 21 percent even though it finished the year
    down 38.5 percent. Unlucky investors with a $10,000 stake in that fund would have suffered
    a loss of $3,850 but would be liable for taxes on a $1,300 distribution. Other taxing
    pitfalls brought out by the Journal included new forms required by the

for mutual fund filers (Schedule D), the probability that tax
    statements from fund groups (Form 1099-Div) will not correctly differentiate between long
    term and short term gains, and late tax statements (as late as April) to shareholders of
    closed-end funds and Real-Estate Investment Trusts.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Taxing capital gains headaches
